subSection.paragraph:
Procerain (Pc) (
Dubey and Jagannadham, 2003a
) and Procerain B (PcB) (Singh et al., 2010) are two major proteases of 

Calotropis procera

(Asclepiadeae tribe of Apocyanaceae family) latex, a widespread tropical plant. Plant parts including the latex has been shown to be useful in treatment of different ailments (
Sharma and Sharma, 2001
; 
Singhal & Kumar, 2009
). Both these enzymes have been characterized extensively for their biochemical properties (
Dubey and Jagannadham, 2003a
; Singh et al., 2010), substrate specificity (
Dubey and Jagannadham, 2003a
; Singh et al., 2010), stability (
Dubey and Jagannadham, 2003a
, 
2003b
; 
Singh et al., 2010b
) and industrial applications (
Dubey and Jagannadham, 2003b
; 
Silva et al., 2020
; 
Silveira et al., 2021
; Abhay Narayan 
Singh and Dubey, 2011
). However, the enzymes are reported to be vulnerable to autolytic degradation (
Dubey and Jagannadham, 2003a
; 
Silveira et al., 2021
; Singh et al., 2010) and hence the purification of the enzymes was reported at 4 
◦
C in the presence of reversible inhibitor like sodium tetrathionate in order to prevent autodigestion during purification process. The autocatalytic inactivation of Pc and PcB have been reported by (
Dubey and Jagannadham, 2003a
) and (Singh et al., 2010), respectively, in presence of reducing agent, 50 mM β- ME. For Pc, it occurs at lower concentration of the protein (
<
0.55 mg
/mL) after prolonged incubation of 48 h at pH 8.0 and 37 
◦
C, while for PcB, it was relatively rapid. PcB loses 50% of activity in 5 h at concentration of
>
0.2 mg
/mL in presence of 50 mM β- ME at 37 
◦
C (
Dubey and Jagannadham, 2003a
; Singh et al., 2010). The same studies, on the other hand, showed high thermal and pH stabilities for these two enzymes. Hence, the mechanism for their autoproteolysis remains elusive and possibly occur in one of the conditions reported earlier for other proteases (
Jomaa et al., 2009
; 
Lee et al., 2007
; 
Maroux and Desnuelle, 1969
; 
Matsumiya et al., 2004
; 
Shapira and Arnon, 1969
; 
Sziegoleit, 1984
). For instance, it could be because of activation of the enzyme or its global denaturation or presence of susceptible cleavage site in structurally unperturbed molecule. In view of all these different possible ways for autolytic degradation of these proteases, it was felt necessary to study the kinetic stability of Pc and PcB in detail with respect to their autoproteolytic degradation. Moreover, since 

Calotropis

cysteine proteases are of great importance due to their potential applications in different industries like food (
Silva et al., 2020
; 
Silveira et al., 2021
; 
Singh and Dubey, 2011
), pharmaceutical (
Rajesh et al., 2005
; 
Ramos et al., 2020
), leather (Lop´ez et al., 2017; 
Silveira et al., 2021
) or detergents (
Singh et al., 2010b
), stability towards auto-degradation becomes all the more important aspect for their practical use.

Thermal denaturation of the enzymes was studied in real-time using differential scanning fluorimetry (DSF). It was carried out for enzymes alone or in combination with GdnHCl and/or β- ME, in presence and absence of E-64 (
Fig. 3A–D
and Supplementary 
Fig. 3A and B
). The denaturation curves of native proteins showed that thermal denaturation of Pc starts at 80 
◦
C, while that of PcB, above 75 
◦
C (
Fig. 3A and B
). The transition temperature of Pc and PcB was not affected due to the presence of E-64. In presence of β- ME, the transition occurred at lower temperatures, with the effect more distinguishable in case of Pc than that in PcB (
Fig. 3A and B
). The increase in fluorescence was higher in case of E-64 inhibited proteins than that of the uninhibited proteins. The relative increase in fluorescence intensity of Pc upon unfolding in presence of β- ME was higher than that observed for native protein, suggesting increased degree of unfolding. Surprisingly, the reverse was observed for PcB, wherein the relative fluorescence intensity decreased in presence of β- ME compared to native protein. Since the thermal denaturation could not be studied in presence of SDS (due to interaction of the dye, SYPRO Orange, with SDS), we used another denaturant GdnHCl to study the same. In case of Pc, for unknown reasons, we could not observe any significant increase in fluorescence irrespective of concentrations of GdnHCl and presence of β- ME and/or E- 
64 in
the mix subjected to DSF studies (Supplementary 
Fig. 3A and B
). Although just a small spur of increase in fluorescence was observed during enzyme alone subjected to denaturation in presence of GdnHCl (Supplementary 
Fig. 1B
), it is not significant to suggest the denaturation temperature in those conditions (Supplementary 
Fig. 1B
). Nevertheless, for PcB, increase in concentration of GdnHCl resulted in decrease in melting temperature and presence of β- ME did not influence thermal denaturation profile of the proteins (
Fig. 3C and D
).

