Effect of different concentrations of β- ME on thermal inactivation (A–D) and autoproteolysis (E & F) of papain-like cysteine proteases. Papain (40 μg), bromelain (100 μg), Pc (60 μg) and PcB (70 μg) were incubated at 50 
◦
C in 20 mM phosphate buffer pH 7.0 containing different concentrations of β- ME in the range of 10–400 mM with final volume 50 μL. The residual activities of the enzymes Pc (
A
), PcB (
B
), bromelain (
C
) and papain (
D
) were determined at intervals up to 2 h using 5 μL of the aliquot and expressed as specific activities. For monitoring autoproteolytic degradation (
E & F
), Pc, PcB, bromelain and papain enzymes in 20 mM phosphate buffer, pH 7.0 were incubated at 50 
◦
C for 1 h (bromelain) and 2 h (Pc, PcB and papain) and the samples were subjected to SDS-PAGE (15%).

subSection.paragraph:
Autocatalysis has been reported for many proteases (
Bickerstaff and Zhou, 1993
; 
Lee et al., 2007
; 
Maroux and Desnuelle, 1969
; 
Matsumiya et al., 2004
; 
Memari et al., 2007
; 
Shapira and Arnon, 1969
; 
Sziegoleit, 1984
; 
Urade et al., 1999
) including cysteine proteases. For few enzymes, autocatalysis can be a mechanism for its activation, like catheptic enzymes (
Verma et al., 2016
). In other enzymes, it is a process leading to irreversible inactivation of the enzyme which is disadvantageous for industrial applications of many enzymes 
viz.
thermolysin or trypsin (
Maroux and Desnuelle, 1969
; 
Matsumiya et al., 2004
). Thus, the phenomenon is of great interest to study the vulnerable cleavage sites in such industrially important enzymes and countering it by protein engineering approach. Although there is no generalized mechanism for autodegradation of proteases, partial unfolding of the enzymes has been reported to be the pre-requisite for their autolysis (
Shapira and Arnon, 1969
; 
Sziegoleit, 1984
). In few cases, however, autodegradation has been reported to occur in conditions optimum for protease activity in which the global protein structure is unperturbed, as in the case of thermolysin (
Matsumiya et al., 2004
), TNA1_POP (
Lee et al., 2007
) and kallikrein (
Memari et al., 2007
), which are known to undergo autolysis at their optimum temperatures. In another example, autoproteolytic inactivation of HtrA protease of 
E. coli
has been suggested to occur by the hyperactivation of the enzyme through allosteric activation by the proteolytic products of its substrates (
Jomaa et al., 2009
). In view of so many different ways the enzymes are reported to undergo autolytic degradation, we studied this phenomenon in two proteases, Pc and PcB, from 

Calotropis procera

.

Azocasein, Sypro-Orange, sodium dodecyl sulphate (SDS), guanidine hydrochloirde (GdnHCl), β- mercaptoethanol (β- ME) were obtained from Sigma (
USA
). CM-Sepharose, Superdex 200 were obtained from Cytiva (
USA
). All other chemicals used were of Analytical Grade.

Homogeneity of the individual protein and molecular weight of the polypeptide was analysed by SDS-PAGE (
Laemmli, 1970
) using 15% (w/v) acrylamide resolving gel and standard proteins as molecular weight markers (Merck Genie, 
India
). Protein denaturation was carried out in the presence of 10–100 μM of E 64 wherever necessary either in sample buffer or individual component of sample buffer.

Pc and PcB share 88.5% sequence identity between them and both of them share about 47% sequence identity with papain (Supplementary 
Fig.2
). Pc and PcB structural models were prepared by homology modelling using SWISS-MODEL server (
Waterhouse et al., 2018
) using default parameters and template as papain structure (PDB id:1PPN) (Supplementary 
Fig. 3
). The molecular dynamics (MD) systems for PcB with and without disulphide bonds were generated using GROMACS 5.1 (
Van Der Spoel et al., 2005
) using CHARMM27 all-atom force field (
Vanommeslaeghe et al., 2010
). The solvated systems were prepared in cubic boxes with one side of 10 Å which was filled with ~13,000 spc 216 water models (
Berendsen et al., 1981
) for each system. Depending upon the overall charge on the protein, an appropriate number of Na 
+
or Cl ions were added to neutralize the system. Additionally, 0.1 M concentration of NaCl was achieved by replacing water molecules. This was followed by energy minimization using the steepest descent algorithm with 1000 kJ/mol/nm tolerance. The temperature and pressure equilibration runs were performed using Berendsen thermostat (
Lemak and Balabaev, 1994
) and Parrinello-Rahman (
Parrinello and Rahman, 1980
) pressure coupling algorithms, respectively. Both the runs were performed using LINCS holonomic constraints on the protein for 10 ns with step size of 2 fs, while using 
1 nm
cut-off distances for both short range electrostatics and van der Waals cut-off during neighbour searching via the PME electrostatics treatment while temperature and pressure equilibration and MD run were per formed using the leap-frog integrator (
Van Gunsteren and Berendsen, 1988
). Final MD run for both PcB with and without disulphide bonds systems was performed for 500 ns (Supplementary 
Fig. 4
and 
5
).
